1
00:00:01,110 --> 00:00:29,852
namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasah namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasah namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasah

2
00:00:30,202 --> 00:00:33,911
homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:36,976 --> 00:00:50,844
So, yesterday we did the hindrances, how to deal with those states of mind which take us away from the object.

4
00:00:53,726 --> 00:00:58,173
even though they're called hindrances they are our teachers aren't they?

5
00:00:59,494 --> 00:01:20,864
because they're there to tell us what's wrong with us and through our instructions we can deal with them in a skillful way so we have to look upon them as welcome enemies something like that we have to open our hearts to our hindrances

6
00:01:24,271 --> 00:01:29,856
Now there's the other side of the equation which is the seven factors of enlightenment and the five spiritual faculties.

7
00:01:30,837 --> 00:01:37,546
And I'm going to try and dovetail them and by the end of the talk you'll be utterly confused.

8
00:01:39,567 --> 00:01:51,882
But I'll try and reduce it to a very simple statement at the end and the best thing is, especially for those who don't know what I'm talking about, is to let it go in one ear and out the other.

9
00:01:53,498 --> 00:02:05,058
Because it's more in the sense of giving a certain confidence and a certain background knowledge which gives you faith, confidence in the process.

10
00:02:07,242 --> 00:02:15,556
And the ground of spiritual practice in terms of advancement is faith, faith.

11
00:02:16,972 --> 00:02:20,355
I was going to say sila, right conduct.

12
00:02:20,896 --> 00:02:24,140
Well of course we always talk about sila and paññā.

13
00:02:24,722 --> 00:02:31,389
So paññā is the wisdom factor and sila refers to the conduct and the one must be mirrored in the other.

14
00:02:33,352 --> 00:02:41,021
But here we're talking more specifically about developing this quality of intuitive insight.

15
00:02:43,145 --> 00:02:50,174
So faith is crucial and the first thing is not to confuse that with belief.

16
00:02:51,015 --> 00:03:03,151
So if we define belief as faith in a statement such as I believe in a god or I don't believe in a god then that's not what the Buddha is talking about when he talks about saddha, faith.

17
00:03:04,354 --> 00:03:11,362
What he's talking about is a sense of confidence, a sense of trust.

18
00:03:11,342 --> 00:03:26,802
And if you think about it, anytime you act, especially those times during our lives when it's a big decision, such as moving house or getting a job elsewhere or...

19
00:03:26,782 --> 00:03:30,770
Forming a relationship or going to live with somebody, marry them.

20
00:03:30,789 --> 00:03:36,117
All those sorts of relationships, all those sorts of occasions demand faith.

21
00:03:37,139 --> 00:03:38,081
That you trust.

22
00:03:39,183 --> 00:03:44,893
You trust in your own decision, you trust in the way that you see things, that you understand things.

23
00:03:44,872 --> 00:03:49,659
and that there's something in the heart which is telling you that this is what you have to do.

24
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:52,022
Otherwise, you just wouldn't do it.

25
00:03:52,743 --> 00:03:58,131
So you can see that the relationship between trust and commitment is crucial.

26
00:03:58,852 --> 00:04:00,693
If you don't trust, you just don't do it.

27
00:04:01,294 --> 00:04:11,088
If you go to a surgeon to have the pimple removed at the end of your nose, and you don't feel right about him or her, then you don't do it.

28
00:04:11,109 --> 00:04:12,129
You go and find somebody else.

29
00:04:14,978 --> 00:04:18,728
So that faith has two qualities.

30
00:04:18,829 --> 00:04:28,076
It has the qualities of understanding and the quality of trust which sort of comes more from the heart.

31
00:04:30,149 --> 00:04:37,560
So this understanding is got merely by listening to Dharma talk, reading.

32
00:04:38,841 --> 00:04:40,785
That's the first sort of understanding we have.

33
00:04:41,665 --> 00:04:44,470
It's a given and it makes sort of sense.

34
00:04:45,911 --> 00:04:52,781
The deeper understanding comes when that becomes our own way, that we've worked it out for ourselves.

35
00:04:53,285 --> 00:05:18,464
So you might hear somebody for instance explain the wheel of dependence origination, this psychology the Buddha taught, and it might initially make sense, but then when you reflect on it, it may begin to make more sense, and you can see that with that more sense there grows that sense of trust, that sort of coming from the heart, that willingness to investigate further.

36
00:05:20,504 --> 00:05:34,362
And of course through the practice of vipassana, what was an intellectual understanding then becomes a direct understanding, and that of course begins to cement the faith, begins to cement it.

37
00:05:37,345 --> 00:06:03,892
and it is said that faith doesn't become unshakeable until we've intuited nibbana so once a person has experienced nibbana then there's no way that that faith can be shaken because now they know for themselves absolutely the teaching of the Buddha is true so it's not a matter then of losing faith anymore in fact the Buddha gives it a different word

38
00:06:03,872 --> 00:06:13,521
For one word it's called an indriya, which is a faculty, and when somebody has an insight into Nibbāna it becomes a bāla, it becomes a strength, unshakable.

39
00:06:17,144 --> 00:06:26,793
And the quality of that understanding, the process, is really just that deepening of understanding, and it has this effect of trust.

40
00:06:27,413 --> 00:06:29,915
Now that trust is coming from the heart, isn't it?

41
00:06:30,115 --> 00:06:32,918
It's something slightly more intuitive.

42
00:06:32,898 --> 00:06:40,990
So there are those people who need to understand the nth degree of the teaching before they dare to trust it.

43
00:06:41,011 --> 00:06:43,014
These are heavy thinkers.

44
00:06:43,954 --> 00:06:54,552
And there are those people who don't need much understanding, they just trust the feeling they have towards a particular teaching or towards a particular teacher.

45
00:06:54,531 --> 00:07:07,899
and that's enough for them you see that feeling of an intuitive feeling that this is right for them most of us of course have to balance the two of them in some sort of proportion

46
00:07:08,504 --> 00:07:12,690
But you can understand that there are some people who just have faith.

47
00:07:13,312 --> 00:07:14,134
They just have faith.

48
00:07:14,954 --> 00:07:23,629
And you can diminish it by calling it blind faith because they can't draw up the arguments.

49
00:07:24,651 --> 00:07:32,384
But it can be just as deeply felt, just as deeply committed as the faith of somebody who can argue their point.

50
00:07:34,254 --> 00:07:42,117
And it was often a criticism that somebody had blind faith.

51
00:07:43,300 --> 00:07:48,636
But if your blind faith is actually in the truth, that's good, isn't it?

52
00:07:50,471 --> 00:07:57,278
I mean, if it actually turns out that what you've got a blind faith in is the absolute truth, it saves you a lot of reading for a start.

53
00:07:58,740 --> 00:08:00,101
I mean, you just get on with the practice.

54
00:08:00,141 --> 00:08:15,737
So this movement of the heart towards faith, you see, is there at the beginning of our practice, and it supports everything that we're doing.

55
00:08:15,716 --> 00:08:17,420
And there's a lovely image given.

56
00:08:17,439 --> 00:08:23,610
I can't remember whether it came from the scriptures, but definitely it's in the Malindi Panya.

57
00:08:24,252 --> 00:08:34,029
So the Malindi Panya were questions and answers given by Nagasena, who was understood to be fully awakened.

58
00:08:34,009 --> 00:08:59,697
some centuries after the Buddha when all the north part of that world was all Greek because Alexander had conquered it so Malindi is actually the Greek king Maninda who would have been around Afghanistan and there he talks about the water purifying gem of the world conquering monarch

59
00:09:00,418 --> 00:09:03,865
In the scriptures you get this myth of the world conquering monarch.

60
00:09:03,945 --> 00:09:17,326
Those of you who know the story of the Buddha, when he was seen by the wise man, he prophesied that this little baby would become either a world conquering monarch or a fully self-enlightened being.

61
00:09:17,807 --> 00:09:25,701
And that's what made his father all upset and made sure that he brought him up to be a world conquering monarch.

62
00:09:25,681 --> 00:09:27,605
That's the story.

63
00:09:27,625 --> 00:09:42,019
So this alter ego runs right through the scriptures that the Buddha could have become this and if he had he would have been this superb leader of the world bringing tremendous good conduct and all that.

64
00:09:41,999 --> 00:09:55,013
So, one of the gems that the person has, one of the things that they have to support that world-conquering manifestation is this water-purifying gem.

65
00:09:55,033 --> 00:10:09,508
So that when all the horses and the camels and the bullock carts have passed over the river with all the men carrying their shields and swords, of course the water is all disturbed, but by dropping this lovely gem into the water, the whole thing just becomes utterly purified.

66
00:10:10,736 --> 00:10:12,678
And that's a lovely image for faith.

67
00:10:12,698 --> 00:10:19,427
Because remember, if you think about it, before you make a decision, there's confusion, isn't there?

68
00:10:20,089 --> 00:10:21,330
There's a sense of confusion.

69
00:10:21,409 --> 00:10:21,791
Shall I?

70
00:10:21,870 --> 00:10:22,451
Shall I not?

71
00:10:23,133 --> 00:10:24,394
There's lots of doubt about.

72
00:10:25,274 --> 00:10:27,317
You don't know whether you will or whether you won't.

73
00:10:28,099 --> 00:10:30,181
You make your lists for and against.

74
00:10:31,001 --> 00:10:34,166
And then suddenly you commit and the whole thing just disappears.

75
00:10:34,506 --> 00:10:35,427
Just like that.

76
00:10:36,100 --> 00:10:41,371
And the heart with all its troubles and its anxieties just gets completely purified.

77
00:10:41,432 --> 00:10:49,129
It just all vanishes and suddenly there's this lovely blossoming of joy in one's commitment.

78
00:10:49,149 --> 00:10:52,235
So it's a lovely image to have that faith.

79
00:10:54,004 --> 00:11:02,996
Now, that faith underpins this paññā, and paññā is this intuitive intelligence.

80
00:11:03,717 --> 00:11:11,349
So it's because we have confidence in this teaching, we have confidence in the practice, that we actually can even start looking.

81
00:11:12,890 --> 00:11:19,099
And that looking, that observing, brings about its own insights, which then strengthens the faith.

82
00:11:19,720 --> 00:11:23,184
And so they tumble over each other into pure awakening.

83
00:11:27,062 --> 00:11:44,143
Now that intuitive intelligence is expressed in the other form, the seven factors of enlightenment, as investigation of dharma, investigation of dharma, dhammavichya.

84
00:11:44,123 --> 00:11:59,903
And when the Buddha is talking about that, remember, if you read the discourse on it, it's basically beginning to look at things the way he saw things.

85
00:11:59,923 --> 00:12:07,633
So we have those three characteristics, transience, not self, and how we create unsatisfactions for ourselves.

86
00:12:07,613 --> 00:12:21,375
but also this business of deconstructing things, all this business around the hindrances, and also all this business around the factors of enlightenment.

87
00:12:21,394 --> 00:12:29,267
So that's all to do with investigating the Dharma as he taught it.

88
00:12:31,120 --> 00:12:36,690
That Dharma is supported, that investigation is supported by equanimity.

89
00:12:37,572 --> 00:12:40,115
Equanimity is one of these funny words really.

90
00:12:42,120 --> 00:12:43,903
It's not the same as calmness.

91
00:12:46,668 --> 00:12:55,102
Equanimity I think is best described as a perfect receptivity.

92
00:12:56,668 --> 00:12:59,131
Now, there's nothing stopping you from receiving.

93
00:12:59,533 --> 00:13:05,059
There's no reaction to what's actually coming at you.

94
00:13:05,080 --> 00:13:14,152
So, if you liken it to a judge, we expect the judge not to get caught up in the funny little arguments of these lawyers.

95
00:13:16,073 --> 00:13:16,975
See, at the head level.

96
00:13:17,916 --> 00:13:23,823
And we don't expect them to get caught up in the anger and emotion of the crowd, baying for blood.

97
00:13:25,035 --> 00:13:50,654
so it's that business of being able to be dispassionate not caught up in and of course as soon as we lift ourselves into the position of the observer it arises naturally because to observe you have to allow whatever is to be observed to manifest and we lose that sense of equanimity

98
00:13:50,753 --> 00:13:56,302
as soon as we dropped into any reaction, wanting, not wanting.

99
00:13:57,845 --> 00:14:03,215
So that equanimity has to be there for the investigation to be clear.

100
00:14:05,077 --> 00:14:13,032
And for the investigation to be clear, the intelligence must be awakened, and we won't do that unless we have faith in the process.

101
00:14:17,821 --> 00:14:27,256
now supporting that you've got concentration which is balanced with effort with proper energy

102
00:14:28,250 --> 00:14:46,690
Concentration again is one of those funny things because normally when you say to somebody, you know, get concentrated or be focused, you expect this sort of real narrowing down, sort of collapse into some sort of tightness, you know.

103
00:14:46,730 --> 00:14:56,080
But concentration in this sense just means being able to keep the attention on the object full stop.

104
00:14:58,456 --> 00:15:08,880
And the effort which is to be developed is just the effort needed to keep the attention on the object.

105
00:15:08,900 --> 00:15:15,856
So if that concentration becomes tight, then you start moving into restlessness.

106
00:15:17,373 --> 00:15:22,277
it begins to shake, you see, and you can't keep your mind on it.

107
00:15:23,197 --> 00:15:27,042
And when that happens, the meditator has to recognize that, you see.

108
00:15:27,522 --> 00:15:46,840
So the restlessness, and this is where the meditation gets, shall we say, a little tricky, because you may be thinking that the restlessness is coming from something arising out of the heart or something, but actually it might be to do because you're trying too hard.

109
00:15:46,820 --> 00:15:51,645
trying to become too concentrated.

110
00:15:51,666 --> 00:16:04,880
So that business of effort and concentration, if you think of a camera, when you focus it, you know the old ones, before they made these little machines, where you had to actually use your fingers.

111
00:16:07,302 --> 00:16:12,168
And if you think of that, you see that's the effort, and then there's the focus, you see.

112
00:16:14,917 --> 00:16:27,336
Now the other side of concentration, when you have too much concentration but not enough energy, is that of course the mind now is like a laser beam, it's facing one way.

113
00:16:27,397 --> 00:16:33,567
And if the energy is not there to support it, then you drop into a state of unconsciousness.

114
00:16:34,659 --> 00:16:58,861
that's not the same as sleep and you'll know the meditator knows when that's happened rather than sleep because the body remains upright because the energy is there alright the concentration is there but because the energy is not supporting it then it's as though the mind just stops as a blank and you wake up

115
00:16:58,841 --> 00:17:28,021
however depending on the power of that concentration it can last for various lengths of time there's a lovely story about a Hindu guru who was an adept at these very high Jhānic absorption states and he gave an instruction to his attendant to get him some water and went to meditate and he went into one of these steps

116
00:17:29,015 --> 00:17:37,065
Ten years later, he comes out of this state and his first words are, where's my water?

117
00:17:38,866 --> 00:17:41,730
And what it's meant, the tale is meant to symbolize that nothing happens.

118
00:17:42,030 --> 00:17:48,298
It's a complete waste of time getting into these blank states.

119
00:17:48,318 --> 00:17:56,929
And it's funny how many people actually believe that meditation is about blanking the mind, about sort of turning it off and ending up in this dead place.

120
00:17:58,343 --> 00:18:11,829
so when that happens we can congratulate ourselves because the concentration is good but then we have to also recognize that the effort there's something wrong with the effort

121
00:18:13,884 --> 00:18:43,892
and normally when you look at it there's been a moment there where you've lost interest where something has lost its empowering of that looking and the whole thing drops when the concentration has become too tight then you have to look at your effort so the effort to gain you see the effort always to achieve and when that happens you have to really remind yourself that to be aware is the achievement that's it there's nothing else to achieve

122
00:18:43,872 --> 00:18:54,742
once you sort of drum that into yourself it does stop you wanting to go beyond the present moment because whenever you want to achieve something it's always in the future isn't it

123
00:18:56,073 --> 00:19:19,701
when you've achieved it you've achieved it but while you're wanting to achieve it's not here it's over there so the mind is always moving ahead of itself so if you find yourself you know when feeling restless and you've got an inkling that it's not really to do because the body feels good and it feels light and it's okay but there's this restlessness

124
00:19:19,681 --> 00:19:45,367
especially not so much at the beginning of a week retreat but maybe within two or three days when you really settle then just see if some idea of getting something has not crept in again the story from the scriptures is of Nanda Nanda was the cousin of the Buddha

125
00:19:46,057 --> 00:20:12,132
and he was really practicing hard and getting nowhere and getting all this sort of restlessness and stuff and so he began to give up and he decided that what he would do in this lifetime was create good karma and then have another go in the next one so the Buddha having heard this or intuiting it appeared by his side and said Nanda what are you doing mate

126
00:20:13,073 --> 00:20:34,692
and he gave the son he said no no he said what you've got to do is you've got to have this effort and he gave the the image of tuning a lute can't remember the proper word for that instrument but it's a lute it's a stringed instrument and he said to get the right pitch

127
00:20:35,550 --> 00:20:39,422
It mustn't be too tight and it mustn't be too loose.

128
00:20:40,144 --> 00:20:41,848
Just getting the right pitch.

129
00:20:43,011 --> 00:20:49,189
And of course, Ananda in no length of time, having got the right pitch, became fully awakened.

130
00:20:52,509 --> 00:21:03,507
Usually these little stories are glossed in the commentary to say things like, Ananda went off to the forest for 25 years and became fully enlightened.

131
00:21:03,527 --> 00:21:08,915
But actually in the scriptures it said he struggled with it and became fully awakened.

132
00:21:09,587 --> 00:21:16,817
So effort is a cheeky one for us because Western culture is about achieving.

133
00:21:17,518 --> 00:21:19,019
It's about achieving, about getting.

134
00:21:19,961 --> 00:21:27,991
And one of the problems of the Vipassana school is that it does put to us certain achievements.

135
00:21:28,011 --> 00:21:28,673
I mean, they're there.

136
00:21:28,712 --> 00:21:34,380
They're called the Vipassananyanas, the insights that come with Vipassana.

137
00:21:34,359 --> 00:21:46,316
And then there are four stages of sanctity for different stream entrants, once returner, non-returner, and then finally this arahat.

138
00:21:46,336 --> 00:21:57,329
And what that does for us, or the way we can look at it so that it doesn't become some sort of achievement, is again this feeling that the path is actually well delineated.

139
00:21:58,136 --> 00:22:03,846
It's not a sort of, we're not on a path which is sort of higgledy-piggledy and it may or may not.

140
00:22:03,866 --> 00:22:13,785
It's actually the path leading to breakthrough is very clearly marked, very clearly marked.

141
00:22:13,805 --> 00:22:21,157
Having said that, the path of the vipassana knowledge is not the only way, not the only way.

142
00:22:21,137 --> 00:22:28,905
And people have achieved amazing insight very quickly, usually because of some great shock.

143
00:22:30,507 --> 00:22:36,794
Somebody close has died or they've fallen off a bridge or something.

144
00:22:36,874 --> 00:22:44,500
Something happens which gives them a shock and it can really pull them out of their particular mind state and turn their lives.

145
00:22:45,321 --> 00:22:49,086
One of the more interesting ones is this near-death experience that people have.

146
00:22:49,066 --> 00:23:04,154
so it's not the I wouldn't say it was the only delineated path you do get slightly different ones in the Mahayana but it's definitely well delineated in this particular

147
00:23:04,134 --> 00:23:04,635
school.

148
00:23:05,175 --> 00:23:14,306
And the whole point about the Mahasi's teaching was that it was meant to be a direct attack on this particular path.

149
00:23:14,346 --> 00:23:22,074
It was meant to be none of this business about trying to get blissed out or having cups of tea when you want.

150
00:23:22,094 --> 00:23:26,478
It was straight on and he was very successful.

151
00:23:28,140 --> 00:23:32,724
So this business of effort and concentration, you see,

152
00:23:33,768 --> 00:24:00,248
the other and those effort by the way and all that comes up in faculties too for those of you who know these things the other combination is calmness and it's badly translated as joy much better translated as interest

153
00:24:01,342 --> 00:24:05,166
So now interest is a funny emotion.

154
00:24:05,186 --> 00:24:08,411
It's the sort that philosophers wonder.

155
00:24:10,093 --> 00:24:15,259
It's a sort of wanting to know, but you can feel it sort of coming from the heart.

156
00:24:15,279 --> 00:24:22,930
And just as an aside, remember, just ask yourself, did you ever have any problem with concentration when you were interested in something?

157
00:24:24,791 --> 00:24:28,277
So that's why, because...

158
00:24:28,577 --> 00:24:55,023
the force of our practice is to awaken the intelligence it seems to me much more beneficial to raise interest rather than to worry about concentration and I'm always amazed how that manifests even in animals this sort of wonder

159
00:24:55,679 --> 00:25:00,424
I was once in a lovely place up in Penang, Malaya.

160
00:25:01,626 --> 00:25:08,496
And there was a plantation up there and I was offered to stay up there at this house which was lived in occasionally.

161
00:25:09,717 --> 00:25:21,231
And it was a lovely evening so I took this table out onto the forecourt there, wanting to sort of lift myself off the ground, you know, because of bugs and stuff, snakes.

162
00:25:22,534 --> 00:25:25,617
And I tied this...

163
00:25:26,222 --> 00:25:53,596
mosquito net to the tree above me and brought me cushions and everything and a cup of coffee and I sat on this table looking out through the mosquito net to the setting sun and as it grew darker and darker I suddenly realized I was facing east

164
00:25:54,538 --> 00:25:59,523
I was a little disappointed.

165
00:25:59,544 --> 00:26:08,192
Now there were these two dogs that every evening would scamper, would chase each other, two very good friends, would chase each other madly around.

166
00:26:08,252 --> 00:26:19,804
And on this particular evening, the one that I was sat out there waiting for the sunset, one of these dogs was late.

167
00:26:20,054 --> 00:26:23,382
And the other one began to pine and cry a little.

168
00:26:24,263 --> 00:26:28,713
And when the dog finally turned up, to my amazement, he sort of ran up.

169
00:26:28,733 --> 00:26:33,865
And when he saw this table with this figure and this...

170
00:26:34,165 --> 00:26:35,328
He stood there and he went...

171
00:26:37,891 --> 00:26:42,077
While the other dog was biting him and doing all sorts of deaf things.

172
00:26:42,097 --> 00:26:42,859
I thought, my goodness.

173
00:26:46,546 --> 00:26:47,989
What amazing sort of intelligence.

174
00:26:49,510 --> 00:26:53,096
Yeah, I must have looked really silly.

175
00:26:53,718 --> 00:26:54,519
To a dog, anyway.

176
00:26:57,525 --> 00:26:58,666
So...

177
00:26:59,946 --> 00:27:03,592
I can't remember why I went into that.

178
00:27:04,353 --> 00:27:05,094
Oh yes, interest.

179
00:27:05,775 --> 00:27:16,128
So this quality of wanting to know, even here, just walking down the street with all these cows and bullocks, it's just amazing.

180
00:27:16,670 --> 00:27:19,473
They just come towards you wanting to know.

181
00:27:20,382 --> 00:27:49,343
